        <h2>The Botox Challenge</h2>
        <p>
          A potential objection: <strong>Botulinum toxin</strong> (Botox) also binds GT1b and enters 
          neurons from nearby tissue â€” without intraneuronal injection. Why would vaccine antigens 
          require direct nerve penetration?
        </p>
        
        <div class="info-box">
          <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">Key Differences</h4>
          <ul class="text-blue-700 text-sm mb-0 space-y-1">
            <li>â€¢ <strong>Effect location:</strong> Botox acts locally at neuromuscular junction; it doesn't need to reach the CNS</li>
            <li>â€¢ <strong>Concentration:</strong> Botox is a purified, highly concentrated toxin</li>
            <li>â€¢ <strong>Efficiency:</strong> Intraneuronal injection may not be <em>required</em>, but dramatically increases transport efficiency for dilute vaccine antigens</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Supporting Evidence: The Injury Proof</h2>
        <p>
          Direct experimental evidence supports the A-series vs B-series functional division:
        </p>
        
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 my-4">
          <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-lg p-4">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-800 mb-2">ğŸ”¬ Biological Proof: C-Fiber GM1 Switch</h4>
            <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
              C-fibers (unmyelinated pain fibers) normally <strong>lack GM1</strong>. After nerve injury, 
              they massively <strong>upregulate GM1</strong> â€” proving that when communication is lost, 
              neurons switch from B-series (shedding) to A-series (storage).
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 text-sm mb-2">
              <strong>NGF reversal:</strong> Treatment with Nerve Growth Factor <em>reversed</em> this 
              phenotype â€” but took <strong>months</strong> of sustained signaling.
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-600 text-xs">
              <a href="https://journals.lww.com/neuroreport/abstract/2001/07030/delayed_administration_of_ngf_reverses_nerve.26.aspx" 
                 class="text-blue-600 hover:underline" target="_blank">
                Rivero-Siri et al. (NeuroReport 2001)
              </a>
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-purple-50 rounded-lg p-4 border border-purple-200">
            <h4 class="font-bold text-purple-800 mb-2">ğŸ§ª Chemical Proof: Neuraminidase Unmasking</h4>
            <p class="text-purple-700 text-sm mb-2">
              When peripheral nerves are treated with <strong>neuraminidase</strong> (which strips 
              sialic acids from complex gangliosides), C-fibers become <strong>intensely labeled</strong> 
              with cholera toxin B (CTB/GM1 marker).
            </p>
            <p class="text-purple-700 text-sm mb-2">
              <strong>Critical observation:</strong> The labeling showed a <strong>dramatic increase 
              specifically in lamina I</strong> of the spinal cord â€” the exact location where orexin 
              neurons project their afferents.
            </p>
            <p class="text-purple-700 text-sm mb-2">
              <strong>Conclusion:</strong> C-fibers normally have complex gangliosides (B-series) 
              that "mask" the GM1 core. Neuraminidase chemically induces the same conversion that 
              injury causes biologically. The lamina I localization proves that transport along 
              C-fibers terminates exactly where orexin neurons are present.
            </p>
            <p class="text-purple-600 text-xs italic">
              Unpublished manuscript, Karolinska Institutet
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="key-concept">
          <div class="key-concept-title">Why This Matters for the Hypothesis</div>
          <p class="mb-3">
            These experiments prove that ganglioside expression is <strong>dynamically regulated</strong>:
          </p>
          <ul class="mb-3 space-y-1">
            <li>
              <strong>C-fibers normally have complex gangliosides</strong> (B-series) â€” they are "invisible" 
              to GM1-binding molecules like cholera toxin
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Injury or enzyme treatment</strong> converts B-series â†’ A-series (GM1) â€” revealing 
              the hidden receptor
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>NGF restores B-series</strong> â€” the system is plastic and neurotrophin-dependent
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mb-0">
            <strong>Implication:</strong> The vaccine antigen doesn't just travel along the neurotrophin highway â€” 
            it enters a system where B-series expression (and thus shedding/release) is tightly coupled to 
            cellular survival signals. The same growth factors that maintain B-series expression are 
            transported via GT1b â€” creating a feedback loop that the vaccine can exploit.
          </p>
        </div>

